default4. Small Claims Track Thresholddefault&#xa0;
defaultThe current limit of £1,000 for personal injury claims means that a large proportion of RTA PI claims are going through the courts, which leaves defendants facing 
defaultsignificantly higher costs and litigation for personal injury claims brought against them.
default 
defaultEnterprise believes that 
defaultraising the threshold for small claims to £5,
default000 would ensure defendants are not saddled with extensive legal costs and litigation for cl
defaultaim
defaults of a relatively low value.
default 
defaultIt would also help reduce the cost of whiplash claims
default overall
default by 
defaultending the requirement
default for costly legal advice in many 
defaultclaims above £1,000.
default&#xa0;
defaultWe also believe that increasing the small claims track is
default fundamental to 
defaultensuring 
defaultfraudulent and exaggerated whiplash claims are challenged
default. By ensuring a far greater number of claims proceed through 
defaultthe small claims track
default, the cost of challenging such claims significantly diminishes. 
defaultIn the past, the cost of challenging 
defaultpotentially 
defaultfra
defaultudulent or
default exaggerated claims has caused insurers to consistently make pre-medical report offers to claimants to offset potential litigation costs of challenging a claim outside the small claims track.
default&#xa0;
defaultThis issue has been longstanding and we would highlight that in 2005-06, the Citizens Advice Bureau, in written evidence to the Constitutional Affairs Committee inquiry into 
defaultThe Courts: small claims
default, suggested that with proper regulation there was a “stron
defaultg argument” that more cases could be dealt under the small claims track, possibly by raising the threshold for personal injury cases to £5,000. The Bureau also said that is supported the principle behind a wide small claims jurisdiction to ensure consumer 
defaultfriendliness and end the requirement to hire expensive legal professionals.
default&#xa0;
defaultWe accept that there are concerns, especially from stakeholders in the personal injury sector, that genuine claimants could be inhibited in 
defaulttheir access to justice and entitlement
default t
defaulto full compensatory amounts
default, however 
defaultwe 
defaultbelieve
default that a number of approaches
default,
default which would offset these concerns,
default 
defaultcould be 
defaulttaken if a decision was made to introduce
default a higher small claims threshold. 
default&#xa0;
defaultWe agree with the Transport Select Committee that the Go
defaultvernment should provide analysis on ways in which the small claims track could be combined with routine submission of expert evidence. We believe that if
default the threshold rise was accompanied by
default measures to make medical reports mandatory for all personal inju
defaultry claims, this would ensure that all cases have received an expert assessment, regardless of the claims track used
default.
default We would also suggest that the introduction of independent and impartial medical boards will provide a rigorous assessment of all claims, wh
defaultich would alleviate c
defaultoncerns over accessibility and proper scrutiny
default for claimants under the small claims track.
default&#xa0;
defaultEn
defaultterprise believes that confidence in a higher threshold would grow after introduction, 
defaultas claimants became more aware of the procedures and system for small claims. It is important that claimants feel comfortable and assured that they can pursue genuine cl
defaultaims without the necessity for costly legal advice and representation. We believe the Government could offset some of these concerns by providing 
defaultinformation and advisory tools. 
defaultEnterprise believes that the Government should explore this approach in conjun
defaultction with an analysis of the impact of the electronic portal on claims management and costs, as suggested by the Committee.
default 
defaultEnterprise 
defaultwould add that it would 
defaultbe willing to work with other stakeholders in
default the car rental sector to provide information and s
defaultupport to those going through the small claims track.
default&#xa0;
defaultEnterprise would be interested to hear from the Government over what approaches it has considered towards the introduction of a higher threshold for the small claims track. Thi
defaults includes 
defaultany 
defaultassessment of the impact of mandatory pre-medical reporting 
defaulton the small claims system 
defaultand 
defaultwe
default agree with the Committee that the Government should provide analysis on ways in which the small claims track could be combined with routine submission of expert e
defaultvidence. 
default&#xa0;
default5. Pre-report claim offersdefault&#xa0;
defaultWe strongly support the 
defaultproposal to introduce a rule which would ensure that a claim can only proceed once a medical examination and report have been completed.
default This would underpin a comprehensive system of medical ex
defaultamination for all whiplash claims and would end the practice of pre-medical offers, which have been linked to the rise of spurious and opportunistic claims. 
defaultTogether with a system of accreditation it would also ensure that claimants 
defaultare 
defaultall equally subject
default to a
default rigorous but f
defaultair examination of their injuries. Enterprise would like to see the Gove
defaultrnment 
defaultundertake a proper assessment on the impact of introducing this rule and explore the possibility of introducing this rule in the package of currently propose
defaultd reforms. 
default&#xa0;
default6. Otherdefault&#xa0;
defaultEnterprise agrees with the Transport Select Committee that the Ministry of Justice should give its view on issues involved in limiting the right to compensation where a claim is shown to be grossly exaggerated. 
defaultWe would suggest that 
defaultclaimants who are attempting any form of deception within a system which is 
defaultintended
default to help the vulnerable 
defaultshould be penalised, including the 
defaultpossibility of forfeiting
default part or 
defaultthe 
defaulttotal sum of their entitled compensation.
default&#xa0;
defaultEnterprise
default also
default strongly
default 
defaultsupports
default the proposal to encourage the use of the Insurance Fraud Register
default and believes that any tool which allows organisations involved in the claims process to share data on known fraudsters to be universally beneficial.
default&#xa0;
default7default. Conclusiondefault&#xa0;defaultWe believe that the Government has made some significant progress in the proposals outlined in the whiplash Command Paper but would like to see 
defaultfar greater detail on the proposals outlined in the paper, such as the accreditation system for medical examiner
defaults. We would urge that not only is greater detail provided on the measures set out in the Command Paper, but the Government expedite the implementation of the main proposals outlined such as the independent medical panels. 
default&#xa0;
defaultIn addition to this we would lik
defaulte to see the Government take proper account of measures suggested which have the potential to curb exaggerated and fraudulent claims and bring down 
defaultlitigation costs whilst
default safeguarding the ability of genuine claimants to receive full compensation. 
defaultThis inc
defaultludes 
defaultthe provision to all
default stakeholders in the 
defaultclaim
defaults process
default equal access to reports 
defaultand 
defaultintroducing a rule to ban pre-medical report offers which fail to examine cases on their proper merits.
